segments.text: Are we back on?
I'm guessing this was probably about midway in that first semester because we were still there in dorm 12.
It wasn't the second semester.
So we determined that the best way to avoid waking them up, our plan was to fill up a couple of balloons with water.
and we had run some tests to make sure this technique would work.

You fill the balloon with water and you put warm water that's as close to body temperature as you can get it so that cold or hot wouldn't initially wake them up if they rolled over and touched the balloon before it went off.
In order to fuse the balloon,
take the end of it where you filled it and you twist it and twist it and twist it and turn it around so it holds against itself but you don't knot it.
And we learned that that will give you about a 10 or 15 minute fuse before the water pressure gradually
unwinds that thing and then it starts to leak and that's going off.
It doesn't explode or anything, it just starts to leak.
That gives you some escape time.
Nobody ever locked their rooms.
In fact, a lot of times, especially in warm weather, the doors were either fully open or cracked open after guys went to bed.
Maybe the windows opened to get some draft and some breeze through the rooms.

This was pre-air conditioning days and so then once you get out you've got to secure the room where the guys can't if they do catch you or if you happen to wake them up so you got a little head start in case there's a chase and so you take a what we call a Jody stick made out of the end of a coke case
And where the handle is on the end of that coat case, you cut a little notch in there that's big enough to fit over the doorknob handle.
And you put that notch over the handle until the handle is in the center of the hand grip and then slide it to that one side.
And from the outside, and there's no way anybody can get the door open until somebody comes and removes the Jody stick.
So that was going to be our escape mechanism.

And so we pulled it off, sneaked in, and of course our hearts were racing like 90 miles an hour as you slip into the room and you lay the water balloons very gently on the edge of the bed and then roll it into where it won't roll off.
One on the top bunk, one on the bottom bunk, and we eased back out, closed the door, and then put the stick on it.
And we did it stealthily enough that we were

back in our room, right across the hall, and one of the reasons we were chosen, we kind of volunteered, but we were chosen to do this was because we didn't think that the psychological warfare that they would think that guys the closest to them would dare try something like this.
And it wasn't necessarily as much for us as it was for some other of our classmates who were being really harassed.
Anyway, we were back in bed and had had a chance to cool down a little bit before we heard the first scream.
And then we heard the pounding on the door to wake people up.
And then finally one of their buddies, probably McGee and Heron, got up and went over there and unjodied the door for them and let them out.
And then all of a sudden, our door flew open.
Two guys came in there and reached under the covers and put their hand on our heart to see if we had a high heartbeat.
They said, Fishery, why is your heart beating so?
I said, oh God, I feel like I'm being raped.
What are you doing in here?
Get away from me.
At that point, I guess they had decided that our reaction was real and we were sleepy enough, we'd had enough cool-down time, that at that point they didn't suspect us.
But he said, you better find out what happened tonight and you better make sure it never happens in your lifetime.
And so they went out and I heard doors opening and they were checking out all the guys to try to find out who had a fast heartbeat or clammy skin or something.

So we got away with it and I don't know if they accused somebody else or if they never found out but we had a couple of additional sophomore meetings and the next day or two and folks on the wall and a lot of intimidation and so forth to try to determine who had done that.
Of course, our answer was, they're not being informed on the highest degree of accuracy.

Anyway, we got away with that and that also helped relieve not only our stress and tension but some of our classmates and actually except for the day or two aftermath from the incident when they were really just livid and off the walls, they kind of calmed down and I kind of suspect that the juniors and seniors might have talked to them about whether they had been out of line or not and their behavior did settle down a little bit.
describe the Babel bombing?
The Babel bombing was against Tom Ralph rest his soul.
He died in Vietnam.
Thomas Ralph.
He was a really gung-ho guy outspoken and boisterous.
I mean he was well known
throughout both the fish and sophomore.
In fact, the whole community knew him.
He was a yell leader his junior year.
Maybe even his, did they have sophomore yell leaders that year?
I don't remember, but he was, I think, elected a yell leader at his earliest opportunity and was really gung-ho, but he had a reputation for harassing the fish that went by his dorm.
He lived over in dorm three and
Since I was studying civil engineering, I had a lot of my classes over on the northeast corner of the campus.

Now when I use references like east, west, north, south, I'm using that basically along the orientation of Highway 6, although I know Highway 6 actually runs northwest and what we call the northeast corner of the campus was actually due north.
from the central part of the campus.
But anyway, we had a lot of classes over there.
So we had to walk by the dorm.
all of the dorms through the quadrangle.
And it seemed like Ralph just made it a practice of standing out there or walking very slowly when he was on his way to class in order to encounter and harass as many freshmen as he could.
And sometimes he was just absolutely unmerciful.
I mean, he was worse than Dabney and Mahan.

and it got to be a topic of conversation among the freshmen about how mean he was and so one night Earl and I looked at each other and said Ralph's gone too far he had harassed some of our guys really badly and so we got a cherry bomb
To make a babbo bomb, you cut a little slit in the side of the full babbo can.
You insert a cherry bomb, or what do we call it, M80 or something, one of the larger size firecrackers, and you put it in there where just the fuse is sticking out.
And then onto the fuse you take a cigarette and put it down so your cigarette is the slow fuse to give you a chance to get away.

And you light the cigarette, you take several puffs on it and then put the opposite end on the fuse and then as the cigarette kind of burns itself down eventually it will get to the fuse and then the bomb goes off.

and uh so we uh uh we got everything in place got the cigarette ready and we actually even had the cigarette lit before we went into the building because we knew we would have a lot of time and we didn't want to spend much time in there now this is what time of night this is probably about uh maybe

two, three o'clock in the morning when everybody's really sound asleep and so we slipped over there and slipped into the building and fortunately Ralph was on the ground floor right near the side hallway.
These dorms had a central hallway running the full length that all of the doors opened off of and then about

a quarter or the third of the way down each of the dorms there was a side hallway that went out to the side entrance doors that opened onto the quadrangle and he lived very near that intersection of one of those side entrances so that made it also very now if he'd been on the fourth floor kind of in the middle of the hallway we might have had second thoughts about it but once we found knew where he lived we figured it was worth the risk

And so once again we slipped in and we put the thing kind of out in the room but in kind of the back corner as far away from their bed as we could so that the cigarette smoke would have dissipated a little bit and wouldn't be something to cause them to wake up and left the thing
kind of on the floor out in the corner.
We wanted it kind of out in the middle of the, a little bit toward the middle of the room so it would have maximum effect in distributing the babbo around the room.
And so, you know, once again in this case we left the door open again to dissipate the cigarette smoke.

we just eased in as a matter of fact I don't remember which one of us placed it and which one of us stood guard but all you needed is one person as a lookout and one person just to go in and set it down turn around and ease back out and then escape and we got away and we were
We were back in our dorm.
We never even heard the explosion because we were back in our dorm at the far opposite corner of the quadrangle.
But we heard the next day from our fish buddies that, hey, y'all here, Tom Ralph got Babel Obama.
Oh, really?
Well, can't think of a more deserving guy.
We just played innocent and never admitted to anyone, at least for several weeks, that we were the perpetrators.
After those, you say for several weeks, what protected you after that?
What kept the secret from getting back to him?
Well, in the first place, we kind of hinted, just hinted that we might have, and even at that, only to other fish.
And they never ratted?
And they never ratted.
And as a matter of fact, I don't know to this day whether Ralph ever knew who had done it.
Now, how did you?
Like when you're walking over there in the middle of the night, what did you wear?
How did you carry the Babel bag?
I really don't remember.
I suspect we were in gym gear, probably black if we had it, just so we wouldn't be all that noticeable.
And one of our...
Oh, I know we had like a six pack of beer, and two or three of the holes in the six pack were already empty, and although Earl and neither of us really drank,
Earl would have a beer occasionally.
I was a Southern Baptist teetotaler, but we had that.
The Babbo was down in there until we got right over outside the room and we lit the cigarette and put it on the fuse.
If we got encountered or caught or anything, we were going to put it down.
We were drunk.
We'd been out too late and we were just staggering back in from the bar.
and on our way back to the dorm so that was going to be our cover story if we got caught either on our way over or on the way back but nobody ever saw us.
Describe the routine in your outfit for a fish in the dining room.
We always went over and marched over in formation until you got just right in front of the door and then they'd say break
and then the fish would stand fast until all the upperclassmen filed in and then the fish would file in and you ate family style.

Everybody went in at once and you got to your tables and they were eight person tables, four people to a side and the end of the table that was on the main, either one of the main aisles or one of the feeder pathway aisles,

the two fish sat on the end of the table that was called the hot corner because that's where the waiter brought all the food and then the fish then would distribute the bowls and platters of food and then of course the seniors always took theirs first and then it went to the juniors and then to the sophomores and then to the fish and

course the fish had to sit at attention to keep the back straight we didn't eat square meals but we did you know you had to answer all of any questions that they ask and you had to respond any kind of services or favors you had to respond and

and and then if you if there's any time left then you got a little chance to eat and then they had cush questions and cush was dessert and uh... what were some of your favorite cush questions that you remember i really don't remember any usually it had to do with campusology uh... like uh... you know who stormed the beaches at normandy or were the cush questions in your outfit factual yes sometimes it had to do with current events
Sometimes it had to do with campusology, stuff that you're supposed to know anyway.
So if you knew the answer.
If you knew the answer, then you qualified for your dessert.
And if you didn't, sometimes they'd give you a second or third chance either to embarrass yourself or to qualify for desserts.
Occasionally, I don't specifically remember ever not qualifying for dessert, but I remember some of my fish buddies did occasionally.
Did they attempt to teach you all the chow hall slang, or did you just pick it up?
No, it was mandatory.
You had to learn it.
That was part of the campusology.
Did you ever, when you got home, forget?
Not any of the inappropriate words for mixed company, but I did.
deal for bread and sky for water and all the other different things.
Occasionally I'd use one of those.
I remember one time I did it at home and I did it premeditated.
It wasn't unintentional just to see the reaction on my dad's face.
He just kind of looked up and kind of grinned.
Mom said, what's that?
What's that mean?
I said, I don't know.
I forget dad what does that mean he told her.
Did you all do any pranks in the dining room?
Occasionally but I don't remember well I do remember one deal fight that's where you take the rolls or bread and wad it up and then

throw it at other units and usually there'd be maybe a vendetta between two units or maybe the unit that had just won the General Moore trophy or had won the graded March pass the week before if they were real arrogant and cocky and smug and overbearing about having won and about being the best and being number one.
Sometimes it would be everybody against them, and everybody would just throw everything in their direction.
But y'all didn't play any pranks on the upperclassmen with their food?
Not that I recall.
We may have, and I might react if I heard some incidents, but I don't recall any off the top of my head.
What was your favorite and least favorite Aggie foods?
I kind of liked it all.
I was not a gourmet or fussy eater.
I eat to live.
I don't live to eat.
So I always found it good, and I always thought when people complained about the food, they just needed something to complain about.
Was there plenty of it?
Yes.
What was special about your outfit, friendships, and what did it take pride in?
I don't know, that doesn't really trigger anything.
We always were good but rarely ever number one.
We were always somewhere in the top four or five or six.

but we never could maybe occasionally we'd get a number two but maybe on a particular weekend march or something or a particular graded march by it seemed like every Thursday evening they'd have a graded march by where you'd form up you'd go down the quadrangle and then march in and there was a reviewing stand and graders
before you got to the Duncan Dining Hall.
We may have occasionally won one of those, but we never won a General Moore or any of the big trophies.
So mostly we concentrated on individual events and activities, and I spent most of my spare time over at the MSC.
I got involved in Memorial Student Center activities.
How did that begin?
Do you remember?
Well, it began with the freshman orientation, the reception for the college president over at TMSC.
And as I recall, was Williams the one that immediately preceded Rutter?
David Morgan.
Morgan, okay, David Morgan, okay.
I believe he was president there and this was probably in September or October it was early in the school year probably was in September where they had the MSC host the fish reception
President and Mrs. Morgan.
So I went over there and following the reception all the different MSC committees had sign up places and display booths about what they did.
That's where I learned about Town Hall and SCONA and great issues and the music committee and the camera committee and all the different things that you could do as a form of extracurricular

activities and leadership and the great issues committee attracted my attention and so I went to the MSC pretty often for one thing it it you escaped a lot of the harassment over in the around the quadrangle and even though I had been a competitive athlete in in high school
I knew I was too small and really wasn't all that good.
I had lettered twice in football and three times in baseball and twice in basketball and once in golf, but I just didn't feel like I was going to be competitive enough to try that at

collegiate level so and I did participate some with our outfit and intramural activities but I spent most of my time at the MSC just because I was more attracted to that and so I ended up being on the great issues committee
How soon before you met Wayne Stark?
Did you know who he was?
Yes, I met him pretty early.
In fact, the very first meeting that I went to the Great Issues Committee, he was an advisor to the Great Issues Committee.
Of course, he was like an ex-officio advisor to all of the committees and could sit in on any of the meetings anytime he wanted, but he delegated some of that.

the really important ones where you're bringing international and nationally known visitors in like the SCONA and great issues and town hall he was almost always present for those committee meetings along with one or two other faculty or former student advisors and I do remember

being told several times at that first committee meeting to relax and participate because I was still a little nervous and tense and whenever there are upperclassmen around you naturally defer and are a little bit reticent to get in and yet in that setting that's different from the regimentation of the cadet corps even though they're cadets also.
But I remember being encouraged several times to relax and

join in and speak up and so I did, made several suggestions and then they needed somebody to write the invitations to the candidates that we had brainstormed, folks who wanted to come to the campus and so I don't remember if I volunteered or if they asked me to do it and in fact it probably was a two or three person subcommittee to do that but I ended up drafting the letters and sending the letters out to attract the speakers
and was pretty successful at that.
I can't remember if it was my freshman year or my sophomore year.
It must have been my sophomore year.
We had gotten to a place where
were coming up on the Christmas holidays and we still had one key speaker due in the spring that we had not filled.
We had asked Dr. Paul Seifel who was a physicist who did earth crust studies and had been North Pole, South Pole and I guess studied the tectonic plate movements and so forth.
and we wanted him to be one of the speakers, but we hadn't heard anything from him, either yes or no.
And so that was one of the occasions for a visit to the green couch.
I think my sophomore year I was vice chairman of the great issues, and I supervised the scheduling and the inviting of the guests.
And so Wayne had me over there, Mr. Stark.
It was in very recent years that I felt like calling him Wayne because all those years, even for years after I graduated, he was always Mr. Stark.
But anyway, he called me in and asked when we expected to hear.
I said, well, I think we've done all we can.
And he concurred.
And so he picked up his phone.

and he dialed and I could tell from the dial it was long distance and he just said hi so and so and called somebody by name he said is Tiger in and I was thinking who in the world is Tiger and the thought crossed my mind I know the congressman from this area is named Tiger Teague Olin Teague was nicknamed Tiger and I thought gee could it be him you know now

and he's really going to high places I mean I was really impressed if he's going to try to get him to help us get a speaker confirmed and so he said we need some help he said I'm sitting here with one of the student leaders and we're

and we need to ask you a favor and then he reached over and he punched the speaker phone and he introduced me to Tiger Teague over the speaker phone and then he said James or Cadet Ray or whatever he called me at the time he said he's got a favor he needs to ask of you and I thought moi and so I kind of stumbled through it and told him what we needed and he said well let me see if I can

call him and encourage him to give y'all a positive answer and so sure enough before we left for Christmas break we had a letter from Dr. Seiple saying he'd be glad to come speak to the great issue series so the MSC was a broadening place but it was also an escape place wasn't it yes and my initial attraction was the escape
Well, I'll say maybe 60-40 escape and 40%.
I really enjoyed it and wanted to be involved in that kind of thing.

But then after three or four meetings, I mean it was 60-40 the other way and then 70, 80, 90, 100% and the escape didn't mean that much to me anymore because as you went along, if you were pretty, if you were
reasonably competent in your marching your formations and your room inspections and kept up with things with your outfit gradually the

the harassment or the training the encouragement the motivation you know kind of died down and especially if your grades were good and you were involved in other activities a lot of times you could use that as an excuse you know if some sophomore wanted to stop you and have you whip out to ten of his buddies and harassing you could say legitimately excuse me sir I'm

I'm going to be late to a class or I'm going to be late to a meeting over at the MSC and most of the time they would honor that and especially if they had no sense that you were abusing it and Fish occasionally might abuse that if they were trying to get out of trouble but most of the time it was legit and so that usually you could do whatever you needed to do
and I got to where I enjoyed that and that was more my contribution to the campus and to the outfit because they also liked each outfit got some

points I don't know for for student participation leadership participation in various activities and so that was encouraged occasionally might get a sourpuss sophomore or junior that was uh maybe getting a little bit jealous of your notoriety and and they might harass you a little bit about it but most of the time it was all positive.
What did you learn from those MSC activities and particularly from Wayne Stark?
for your future?
Well, horizon broadening, the willingness to or being ready and confident that if you've got a chance to take part in a big enterprise to do it because that's a...
